\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## T-011@20260502T001347Z (2026-05-02T01:36:00Z)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Reason:** StoryBeat wire-shape and deploy-side engine assumptions\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Details:** Exploration found no deploy-side `cypherclaw.narrative.engine.NarrativeEngine` package in this PromptClaw checkout; production still needs the package deployed on the CypherClaw host. T-011 therefore follows the existing narrative API lazy-import pattern and tests through injected fake engines. Deniable's `world_bridge.py` treats the `StoryBeat` response as an engine-owned raw payload with required `id`, `cycle_number`, and `arc_position`, so the endpoint should serialize the in-process beat without adding null/default response-model fields. No new dependencies, database columns, or migrations are required. The generated hardening bullets about SenseWeave self-critique/resource-governor wiring and daemon identity startup are unrelated to the `/beats/next` wrapper; startup identity is already covered by existing narrative API main/startup tests.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"}\\\\\\\\n./sdp/logs/Lead_T-003_20260427T001208Z_1777253601.log:- Enforce behavioral regression tests before completion: Startup hardening gap: `my-claw/tools/cypherclaw_daemon.py` does not call `bootstrap_identity()` before startup announcement and main loop, while this path is still part of the runnable daemon entry points (`my-claw/docs/PROJECT_GUIDE.md` and system scripts/tests reference it), so first-boot identity creation is not guaranteed in that mode. Severity: blocking..\\\\\\\\n./sdp/logs/Lead_T-003_20260427T001208Z_1777253601.log:{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"message\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"timestamp\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"2026-04-27T01:33:24.732Z\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"role\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"user\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"content\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"# Task T-003@20260427T001208Z: Implement `ModalClient` parallel implementation of `GenerationClient` Protocol.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `client_modal.py` defines `ModalClient` satisfying `GenerationClient` Protocol<br/>- Uses Modal Python SDK to invoke a deployed MusicGen function<br/>- Cost computed from Modal prediction metadata × per-second A10G rate<br/>- Mocked test asserts Protocol parity with `ReplicateClient`<br/>- Real Modal call gated behind `@pytest.mark.live_modal` (skipped by default)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n**Tier:** T2 — Standard (New feature / moderate refactoring)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Instructions\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nRead the project's ADP documentation and understand existing patterns before making changes.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n**ADP Phases:** Explore → Specify → Test → Implement → Verify → Document\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 0: Explore\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Read all files in the affected area of the codebase.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Identify existing patterns, naming conventions, and architectural decisions.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Review related tests to understand expected behavior.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Update progress.md with exploration findings.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 1: Specify\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Write a specification to `specs/t-003@20260427t001208z-spec.md`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Include: problem statement, technical approach, edge cases, acceptance criteria.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Each acceptance criterion must have a VERIFY command.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 2: Test Development\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Write tests BEFORE implementation, derived from the specification.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Tests must FAIL before implementation (Red phase).\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- After this phase, test files are LOCKED — do not modify assertions.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 3: Implement\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Implement the minimum code needed to pass all tests.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- One sub-task at a time, commit each logical unit.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Type hints on all function signatures.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Follow existing patterns.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n### Phase 4: Verify & Document\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Run full test suite and quality checks.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Update CHANGELOG.md, progress.md.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Rules\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- No questions — document assumptions in ESCALATIONS.md.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Do not modify locked test assertions.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Log new dependencies to ESCALATIONS.md.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Commit per sub-task: `feat(scope): summary [T-003@20260427T001208Z]`\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Common Pitfalls (from recurring verify feedback)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nThese are the top reasons tasks get PASS WITH NOTES instead of clean PASS.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nAvoid them on the first attempt:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Always include a migration** when adding or modifying database columns.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  A new model or column without a migration is a deployment gap.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Commit all changes** before the verify phase begins. Uncommitted work\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  is flagged as blocking by the verifier.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Stay in scope** — only commit work under this task's ID. Do not bundle\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  changes from adjacent subtasks or refactor unrelated code.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Add indexes on new FK columns** in `__table_args__` when adding\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  foreign key relationships.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- **Keep CHANGELOG entries consistent** with actual behavior. Do not copy\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  descriptions from other tasks or specs without verifying they match\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n  the implemented code.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Validation\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nRun before final commit:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n```bash\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\npip install -e '.[dev]' && pytest tests/ -x && ruff check src/ tests/ && mypy src/\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n```\\\\